he families considered include those of several famous naval figures, including Philip Broke, Matthew Flinders and George Bass, and also the families of "lower deck" seamen, some of whom could not write for themselves and where data has been gleaned from previously unexplored petitions. The information provided contributes to a wider understanding of gender roles, especially masculinity, in the period and to eighteenth-century social and cultural history more broadly. Moreover, as insights into the intimate and emotional details of family life, especially between husbands and wives, aredifficult to discover in any historical period (such intimacy being rarely recorded), the details presented here constitute a rare resource. Ellen Gill completed her doctorate at the University of Sydney.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNaviesxFamily relationshipszGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aNaviesxFamily relationshipszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aWar and familieszGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aWar and familieszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aMaritime History. 4aMilitary History. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aarmy.  ahistory of war.  aintimacy.  amarines.  amemorial.  amilitary marriages.  amilitary.  anaval academy.  anaval careers.  anaval marriages.  anavy.  apatriotism.  aseamen.  aveterans.  awar and duty.  awar and peace.  awar families.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311143131440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204824440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782048244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782048244/original  a978-3-11-143131-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGr